  abstract = {Peatlands are strategic areas for climate change mitigation because of their matchless carbon stocks. Drained peatlands release this carbon to the atmosphere as carbon dioxide (CO\textsubscript{2}). Peatland rewetting effectively stops these CO\textsubscript{2} emissions, but also re-establishes the emission of methane (CH\textsubscript{4}). Essentially, management must choose between CO\textsubscript{2} emissions from drained, or CH\textsubscript{4} emissions from rewetted, peatland. This choice must consider radiative effects and atmospheric lifetimes of both gases, with CO\textsubscript{2} being a weak but persistent, and CH\textsubscript{4} a strong but short-lived, greenhouse gas. The resulting climatic effects are, thus, strongly time-dependent. We used a radiative forcing model to compare forcing dynamics of global scenarios for future peatland management using areal data from the Global Peatland Database. Our results show that CH\textsubscript{4} radiative forcing does not undermine the climate change mitigation potential of peatland rewetting. Instead, postponing rewetting increases the long-term warming effect through continued CO\textsubscript{2} emissions.},
